  {
    "@id": "https://purl.org/hed/tag#Semiology-dyscognitive",
    "@type": [
      "https://purl.org/hed#HedTag"
    ],
    "http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment": [
      {
        "@value": "The term describes events in which (1) disturbance of cognition is the predominant or most apparent feature, and (2a) two or more of the following components are involved, or (2b) involvement of such components remains undetermined. Otherwise, use the more specific term (e.g., mnemonic experiential seizure  or hallucinatory experiential seizure). Components of cognition: ++ perception: symbolic conception of sensory information ++ attention: appropriate selection of a principal perception or task ++ emotion: appropriate affective significance of a perception ++ memory: ability to store and retrieve percepts or concepts ++ executive function: anticipation, selection, monitoring of consequences, and initiation of motor activity including praxis, speech."
      }
    ],
    "http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label": [
      {
        "@value": "Semiology-dyscognitive"
      }
    ],
    "https://purl.org/hed#hasHedParent": [
